3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* tls_dh
6/* SUMMARY
7/* Diffie-Hellman parameter support
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* #define TLS_INTERNAL
10/* #include <tls.h>
11/*
12/* void tls_set_dh_from_file(path, bits)
13/* const char *path;
14/* int bits;
15/*
16/* int tls_set_eecdh_curve(server_ctx, grade)
17/* SSL_CTX *server_ctx;
18/* const char *grade;
19/*
20/* DH *tls_tmp_dh_cb(ssl, export, keylength)
21/* SSL *ssl; /* unused */
22/* int export;
23/* int keylength;
24/* DESCRIPTION
25/* This module maintains parameters for Diffie-Hellman key generation.
26/*
27/* tls_tmp_dh_cb() is a call-back routine for the
28/* SSL_CTX_set_tmp_dh_callback() function.
29/*
30/* tls_set_dh_from_file() overrides compiled-in DH parameters
31/* with those specified in the named files. The file format
32/* is as expected by the PEM_read_DHparams() routine. The
33/* "bits" argument must be 512 or 1024.
34/*
35/* tls_set_eecdh_curve() enables ephemeral Elliptic-Curve DH
36/* key exchange algorithms by instantiating in the server SSL
37/* context a suitable curve (corresponding to the specified
38/* EECDH security grade) from the set of named curves in RFC
39/* 4492 Section 5.1.1. Errors generate warnings, but do not
40/* disable TLS, rather we continue without EECDH. A zero
41/* result indicates that the grade is invalid or the corresponding
42/* curve could not be used.
43/* DIAGNOSTICS
44/* In case of error, tls_set_dh_from_file() logs a warning and
45/* ignores the request.
46/* LICENSE
47/* .ad
48/* .fi
49/* This software is free. You can do with it whatever you want.
50/* The original author kindly requests that you acknowledge
51/* the use of his software.
52/* AUTHOR(S)
53/* Originally written by:
54/* Lutz Jaenicke
55/* BTU Cottbus
56/* Allgemeine Elektrotechnik
57/* Universitaetsplatz 3-4
58/* D-03044 Cottbus, Germany
59/*
60/* Updated by:
61/* Wietse Venema
62/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
63/* P.O. Box 704
64/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
65/*--*/

91 /*
92 * Compiled-in DH parameters. Used when no parameters are explicitly loaded
93 * from a site-specific file. Using an ASN.1 DER encoding avoids the need
94 * to explicitly manipulate the internal representation of DH parameter
95 * objects.
96 *
97 * 512-bit parameters are used for export ciphers, and 2048-bit parameters are
98 * used for non-export ciphers. The non-export group is now 2048-bit, as
99 * 1024 bits is increasingly considered to weak by clients. When greater
100 * security is required, use EECDH.
101 */
102
103 /*-
104 * Generated via:
105 * $ openssl dhparam -2 -outform DER 512 2>/dev/null |
106 * hexdump -ve '/1 "0x%02x, "' | fmt
107 * TODO: generate at compile-time. But that is no good for the majority of
108 * sites that install pre-compiled binaries, and breaks reproducible builds.
109 * Instead, generate at installation time and use main.cf configuration.
110 */
111static unsigned char dh512_der[] = {
112 0x30, 0x46, 0x02, 0x41, 0x00, 0xd8, 0xbf, 0x11, 0xd6, 0x41, 0x2a, 0x7a,
113 0x9c, 0x78, 0xb2, 0xaa, 0x41, 0x23, 0x0a, 0xdc, 0xcf, 0xb7, 0x19, 0xc5,
114 0x16, 0x4c, 0xcb, 0x4a, 0xd0, 0xd2, 0x1f, 0x1f, 0x70, 0x24, 0x86, 0x6f,
115 0x51, 0x52, 0xc6, 0x5b, 0x28, 0xbb, 0x82, 0xe1, 0x24, 0x91, 0x3d, 0x4d,
116 0x95, 0x56, 0xf8, 0x0b, 0x2c, 0xe0, 0x36, 0x67, 0x88, 0x64, 0x15, 0x1f,
117 0x45, 0xd5, 0xb8, 0x0a, 0x00, 0x03, 0x76, 0x32, 0x0b, 0x02, 0x01, 0x02,
118};
119
120 /*-
121 * Generated via:
122 * $ openssl dhparam -2 -outform DER 2048 2>/dev/null |
123 * hexdump -ve '/1 "0x%02x, "' | fmt
124 * TODO: generate at compile-time. But that is no good for the majority of
125 * sites that install pre-compiled binaries, and breaks reproducible builds.
126 * Instead, generate at installation time and use main.cf configuration.
127 */
128static unsigned char dh2048_der[] = {
129 0x30, 0x82, 0x01, 0x08, 0x02, 0x82, 0x01, 0x01, 0x00, 0xbf, 0x28, 0x1b,
130 0x68, 0x69, 0x90, 0x2f, 0x37, 0x9f, 0x5a, 0x50, 0x23, 0x73, 0x2c, 0x11,
131 0xf2, 0xac, 0x7c, 0x3e, 0x58, 0xb9, 0x23, 0x3e, 0x02, 0x07, 0x4d, 0xba,
132 0xd9, 0x2c, 0xc1, 0x9e, 0xf9, 0xc4, 0x2f, 0xbc, 0x8d, 0x86, 0x4b, 0x2a,
133 0x87, 0x86, 0x93, 0x32, 0x0f, 0x72, 0x40, 0xfe, 0x7e, 0xa2, 0xc1, 0x32,
134 0xf0, 0x65, 0x9c, 0xc3, 0x19, 0x25, 0x2d, 0xeb, 0x6a, 0x49, 0x94, 0x79,
135 0x2d, 0xa1, 0xbe, 0x05, 0x26, 0xac, 0x8d, 0x69, 0xdc, 0x2e, 0x7e, 0xb5,
136 0xfd, 0x3c, 0x2b, 0x7d, 0x43, 0x22, 0x53, 0xf6, 0x1e, 0x04, 0x45, 0xd7,
137 0x53, 0x84, 0xfd, 0x6b, 0x12, 0x72, 0x47, 0x04, 0xaf, 0xa4, 0xac, 0x4b,
138 0x55, 0xb6, 0x79, 0x42, 0x40, 0x88, 0x54, 0x48, 0xd5, 0x4d, 0x3a, 0xb2,
139 0xbf, 0x6c, 0x26, 0x95, 0x29, 0xdd, 0x8b, 0x9e, 0xed, 0xb8, 0x60, 0x8e,

141 0xe6, 0x0c, 0x22, 0xc9, 0x35, 0xb3, 0x1b, 0x96, 0xbb, 0x0a, 0x5a, 0xc3,
142 0x09, 0xa0, 0xcc, 0xa5, 0x40, 0x90, 0x0f, 0x59, 0xa2, 0x89, 0x69, 0x2a,
143 0x69, 0x79, 0xe4, 0xd3, 0x24, 0xc6, 0x8c, 0xda, 0xbc, 0x98, 0x3a, 0x5b,
144 0x16, 0xae, 0x63, 0x6c, 0x0b, 0x43, 0x4f, 0xf3, 0x2e, 0xc8, 0xa9, 0x6b,

151 0xab, 0x02, 0x01, 0x02,

154 /*
155 * Cached results.
156 */
157static DH *dh_1024 = 0;
158static DH *dh_512 = 0;
159
160/* tls_set_dh_from_file - set Diffie-Hellman parameters from file */
161
162void tls_set_dh_from_file(const char *path, int bits)
163{
164 FILE *paramfile;
165 DH **dhPtr;
166
167 switch (bits) {
168 case 512:
169 dhPtr = &dh_512;
170 break;
171 case 1024:
172 dhPtr = &dh_1024;
173 break;
174 default:
175 msg_panic("Invalid DH parameters size %d, file %s", bits, path);
176 }
177
178 /*
179 * This function is the first to set the DH parameters, but free any
180 * prior value just in case the call sequence changes some day.
181 */
182 if (*dhPtr) {
183 DH_free(*dhPtr);
184 *dhPtr = 0;
185 }
186 if ((paramfile = fopen(path, "r")) != 0) {
187 if ((*dhPtr = PEM_read_DHparams(paramfile, 0, 0, 0)) == 0) {
188 msg_warn("cannot load %d-bit DH parameters from file %s"
189 " -- using compiled-in defaults", bits, path);
190 tls_print_errors();
191 }
192 (void) fclose(paramfile); /* 200411 */
193 } else {
194 msg_warn("cannot load %d-bit DH parameters from file %s: %m"
195 " -- using compiled-in defaults", bits, path);
196 }
197}
198
199/* tls_get_dh - get compiled-in DH parameters */
200
201static DH *tls_get_dh(const unsigned char *p, size_t plen)
202{
203 const unsigned char *endp = p;
204 DH *dh = 0;
205
206 if (d2i_DHparams(&dh, &endp, plen) && plen == endp - p)
207 return (dh);
208
209 msg_warn("cannot load compiled-in DH parameters");
210 if (dh)
211 DH_free(dh);
212 return (0);
213}
214
215/* tls_tmp_dh_cb - call-back for Diffie-Hellman parameters */
216
217DH *tls_tmp_dh_cb(SSL *unused_ssl, int export, int keylength)
218{
219 DH *dh_tmp;
220
221 if (export && keylength == 512) { /* 40-bit export cipher */
222 if (dh_512 == 0)
223 dh_512 = tls_get_dh(dh512_der, sizeof(dh512_der));
224 dh_tmp = dh_512;
225 } else { /* ADH, DHE-RSA or DSA */
226 if (dh_1024 == 0)
227 dh_1024 = tls_get_dh(dh2048_der, sizeof(dh2048_der));
228 dh_tmp = dh_1024;
229 }
230 return (dh_tmp);
231}
232
233int tls_set_eecdh_curve(SSL_CTX *server_ctx, const char *grade)
234{
235#if OPENSSL_VERSION_NUMBER >= 0x1000000fL && !defined(OPENSSL_NO_ECDH)
236 int nid;
237 EC_KEY *ecdh;
238 const char *curve;
239 int g;
240
241#define TLS_EECDH_INVALID 0
242#define TLS_EECDH_NONE 1
243#define TLS_EECDH_STRONG 2
244#define TLS_EECDH_ULTRA 3
245 static NAME_CODE eecdh_table[] = {
246 "none", TLS_EECDH_NONE,
247 "strong", TLS_EECDH_STRONG,
248 "ultra", TLS_EECDH_ULTRA,
249 0, TLS_EECDH_INVALID,
250 };
251
252 switch (g = name_code(eecdh_table, NAME_CODE_FLAG_NONE, grade)) {
253 default:
254 msg_panic("Invalid eecdh grade code: %d", g);
255 case TLS_EECDH_INVALID:
256 msg_warn("Invalid TLS eecdh grade \"%s\": EECDH disabled", grade);
257 return (0);
258 case TLS_EECDH_NONE:
259 return (1);
260 case TLS_EECDH_STRONG:
261 curve = var_tls_eecdh_strong;
262 break;
263 case TLS_EECDH_ULTRA:
264 curve = var_tls_eecdh_ultra;
265 break;
266 }
267
268 /*
269 * Elliptic-Curve Diffie-Hellman parameters are either "named curves"
270 * from RFC 4492 section 5.1.1, or explicitly described curves over
271 * binary fields. OpenSSL only supports the "named curves", which provide
272 * maximum interoperability. The recommended curve for 128-bit
273 * work-factor key exchange is "prime256v1" a.k.a. "secp256r1" from
274 * Section 2.7 of http://www.secg.org/download/aid-386/sec2_final.pdf
275 */
276
277 if ((nid = OBJ_sn2nid(curve)) == NID_undef) {
278 msg_warn("unknown curve \"%s\": disabling EECDH support", curve);
279 return (0);
280 }
281 ERR_clear_error();
282 if ((ecdh = EC_KEY_new_by_curve_name(nid)) == 0
283 || SSL_CTX_set_tmp_ecdh(server_ctx, ecdh) == 0) {
284 EC_KEY_free(ecdh); /* OK if NULL */
285 msg_warn("unable to use curve \"%s\": disabling EECDH support", curve);
286 tls_print_errors();
287 return (0);
288 }
289 EC_KEY_free(ecdh);
290#endif
291 return (1);
292}

298 tls_tmp_dh_cb(0, 1, 512);
